236. se expediant seems to occur only here, but has no doubt the same sense as the simple empediant: comp. below v. 276, sepenetrare. res expedit means ‘the affair takes a (cer- tain) course’: Amph. 1 3, 23 nequiter paene expedivit prima parasitatio ‘my first appear- anco in the part of parasite had nearly been a sad failure'; ib. prol. 5, ut res vostrorum om- nium bene expedire voltis ‘as you all wish your affairs to turn out well ².
